    <!-- OCR prep modes explanation -->
    <string name="ocr_explain_prep_modes">Explain recognition modes</string>
    <string name="ocr_prep_modes_title">Recognition modes: simple explanation</string>
    <string name="ocr_prep_modes_message">There are two ways to feed images into the OCR engine:\n\n• Original (no
        preprocessing) — fastest. We send the photo as-is. Best for already clean, high-contrast scans. May miss faint
        or noisy text.\n\n• OpenCV Robust — rebuilt for maximum accuracy on difficult pages. It deskews, normalizes
        shadows/illumination, applies edge‑preserving denoise and smart upscaling. Importantly, it feeds Tesseract a
        high‑quality grayscale image (not hard black/white) to preserve fine details like loops in “o” and small
        digits. Best accuracy on tough pages; slower and uses more memory. Recommended default for most photos.\n\nOCR
        Post-Processing: Corrects typical recognition errors like confusions (0↔O, 1↔l↔I, rn↔m) and checks uncertain
        words against a dictionary. Enabled by default; disable for technical codes or serial numbers.
    </string>

